 Enlarge





                Joah Spearman, CEO of Localeur, enjoying a game of Ping-Pong at Parlor and Yard.            

                Arnold Wells            








 



Joah Spearman is the poor man‚Äôs CEO and startup founder ‚Äî on purpose.
Like a superstar athlete who takes a hometown discount to keep a championship-contending team together, the leader and creator of Localeur Inc. has chosen to collect what amounts to an average annual salary of $32,400 since he launched the venture in 2013.













 Enlarge






                            Joah Spearman, CEO of Localeur, enjoying a game of Ping-Pong at Parlor and Yard.                        
Arnold Wells










 


Localeur is an Austin-based company that operates like an online travel guide with destination information provided by local residents. It exists in 50 cities worldwide.
‚ÄúIt‚Äôs more important that I keep Localeur alive and thriving than to increase my salary,‚Äù said Spearman, 34. ‚ÄúI paid myself $36,000 in 2013 and 2014; $15,000 in 2015 and 2016; and now am paying myself $60,000.‚Äù
Even with that self-given raise, however, Spearman the boss hasn‚Äôt paid Spearman the employee for three consecutive pay periods through mid-June, he said, because ‚Äúwe are in the final few months of pushing to become cash-flow positive.‚Äù
Profitable, in other words.
‚ÄúI‚Äôm repaying the people who have believed in me throughout my entire professional journey,‚Äù Spearman said of the company's 49 investors, several of whom he worked for in previous jobs.
They include Austin-based WP Engine Inc. CEO Heather Brunner; Jeff Eller, founder of The Jeff Eller Group LLC in Austin and former deputy assistant and director of media affairs for President Bill Clinton; and Brett Hurt, founder and CEO of Austin-based Data.world Inc.
Here‚Äôs the thing about Spearman: He doesn‚Äôt need the stuff many Americans see as essential. For example, Spearman sold his car recently to help Localeur cover its payroll.




Frugal habits acquired over a lifetime combined with savings he accumulated during stints at a few high-paying gigs prior to forming Localeur is another way Spearman is able to survive on such a low income in Austin.
‚ÄúI grew up poor,‚Äù he said of his first 18 years, spent in Killeen, Texas, and Greenville, South Carolina. ‚ÄúI had a single mom who raised three boys on food stamps and by working two jobs."

To earn some money, Spearman began working at age 11, mowing lawns. When he was 12, he created a second revenue stream by selling bubble gum to classmates.
So it has gone to the present day. He never stopped thinking of new ways to make sure he had money coming in.
Spearman is the first person in his immediate family to graduate from college. He knew he wasn‚Äôt attending unless he paid for it himself, so Spearman applied for more than 100 scholarships, got about 30 of them worth roughly $100,000 and graduated from the University of Texas at Austin in 2005.
Between commencement and Localeur‚Äôs liftoff, Spearman held several high-profile, high-intensity positions:
‚Ä¢ He was the primary speechwriter for David Paulison, director of the Federal Emergency Management Agency in 2005 and 2006. Sometimes he‚Äôd see President George W. Bush and Secretary of Homeland Security Michael Chertoff using what he wrote to answer Anderson Cooper‚Äôs questions on CNN. And he often attended briefings that included at least one of those three men.
‚Ä¢ He was director of operations and strategic initiatives in 2011-2012 for Bazaarvoice Inc., which powers consumer product reviews online.
Spearman also co-wrote a book, published in 2010, ‚ÄúReal Role Models,‚Äù which profiled ‚Äú23 high-level black professionals‚Äù for the purpose of introducing African-American youth to role models outside the sports and entertainment sectors.




 


And he founded Sneak Attack LLC, a sneaker and urban-fashion company in 2009, and Style X, the official style segment of South by Southwest.
‚ÄúI felt my creativity wasn‚Äôt activated until I became an entrepreneur,‚Äù Spearman said of his decision to leave corporate America and begin his own ventures. ‚ÄúMy plan was to found one business every year until one stuck.‚Äù
How do you relieve stress? I actually like stress and high pressure. But for fun I run long-distance races, like half-marathons, go bowling and play a lot of Ping-Pong. I have a Ping-Pong table in my front yard.
If you could be any superhero, who would you be? Wolverine (of the X-Men). He has a code. He‚Äôs not perfect like Superman. He‚Äôs not wealthy like Batman. He‚Äôs usually on the side of good and right.
If you could play any sport professionally and be one of the best, which sport would you pick and what position would you play? Pitcher for the Atlanta Braves.
If you could be a Division I scholarship athlete at any school, what sport would you choose and what school? Runner at the University of Oregon. I love Steve Prefontaine.
Who would win in a fight: Homer Simpson from ‚ÄúThe Simpsons‚Äù or Mr. Mackey from ‚ÄúSouth Park‚Äù? Homer Simpson. He did OK against Peter Griffin on Family Guy in that episode, ‚ÄúThe Simpsons Guy.‚Äù
What‚Äôs your favorite meal to eat at a restaurant? Breakfast.
What‚Äôs your favorite Austin restaurant? Uchiko.
What‚Äôs your dream car? Ferrari 458 Spider.
If you could have dinner with anyone whom you haven‚Äôt met, who would it be? Donald Glover. (He is a Grammy-award nominated rapper and actor who will play a young Lando Calrissian in an upcoming ‚ÄúStar Wars‚Äù movie, plus he's a comedian and was a writer for the TV show ‚Äú30 Rock.‚Äù)

Joah Spearman
Age: 34
Fianc√©: Susannah
Residence: Austin
Hometowns: Killeen, Texas, and Greenville, South Carolina
Education: Bachelor of Science in public relations, University of Texas at Austin, 2005
Email: Joah@localeur.com

Mike Cronin covers the technology, startup and finance sectors in Central Texas for the Austin Business Journal.













